                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d727">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">390D.11/71: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Beirut</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steger</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Beirut</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-03T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 3, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 3—10:34 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s November 1, 5 p.m. Discussed yesterday with High Commission
                    situation created by Franco-Turkish Agreement and have received strongest verbal
                    assurances that American rights as laid down in Gouraud-Knabenshue Agreement
                    will not be modified and that Foreign Affairs Ministry will be requested to make
                    situation clear in new instructions to consular officers in the United States.
                    Written assurances have been promised for the near future.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steger</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
